Learning Objectives:
~ ASCII
~ Unicode
~ UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32
~ How emoji is encoded
~ And what causes gibberish characters

Notes:
- ASCII is a 7-bit standard that defines 128 characters covering English letters, digits, and basic punctuation.
- Unicode is a universal character encoding standard. It assigns unique code points to characters from all modern and historical writing systems worldwide.

** Completed a lab to learn about ASCII and its limitations, and about Unicode and three encoding standards: UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32. Also explored how Unicode enables us to cover not only the world’s languages but also symbols such as chess pieces and emojis.

Conclusion - learned that characters are just numbers with agreed meanings called an encoding.
